\par }{\fs24\lang2057 <#/>CAN Third World countries improve faster by simply importing appropriate 
technology? <#/>If so, is it, therefore, no longer necessary for the developing world to embark on intensive research and development investments because they can just transfer what has already been discovered? <#/>Read this write-up based on what Prof. G
. K. Munishi recently told the Third Annual Scientific Seminar organised by the Tanzania Commission for Science and technology.
\par }\pard \qj\nowidctlpar\tx8364\tx8505\tx9072\adjustright \cbpat8 {\fs24\lang2057 <#/>TECHNOLOGY is the aspect of applying scientific discoveries to increase quantity and improve quality. <#/>A system is a dyna
mic, organic whole which is composed of interdependent parts or subsystems.
\par <#/>Educational systems are closely-related to demands in industry, agriculture and other sectors of the economy. <#/>A system approach applied in the global management of Science
 (S) and Technology (T) intends to examine the processes and stumbling blocks in the transfer of S & T for development.
\par }\pard \qj\nowidctlpar\tx8364\tx8505\adjustright {\fs24\lang2057 <#/>A working basis assumption exists that claims that development processes necessarily need science and technology as inputs. <#/>If 
S & T could be regarded as universal goods, things would be easier for a country such as Tanzania. <#/>Arguments on the use of S & T assume that principle but not so in reality. <#/>S & T transfer is much a function of or is dependent upon the overall fre
edom or autonomy on the part of those operating within the S & T systems universally.
\par <#/>Those who first discover scientific knowledge that can be put into practice for solving problems tend to exercise autonomy and ownership rights. <#/>Possibly countrie
s which own Science and technological packages tend to politically manipulate that the transfers meet the political and economic objectives of the owning countries ... sometimes at the expense of the country to which the technology packages are being t
ransferred.
\par <#/>Thus contrary to the assumed ,systems' free input-output flows, in the transfer of S & T, the systems themselves are constrained domestically and internationally.
\par <#/>There is an argument that developing countries can improve faster by wa
y of importing appropriate technology. <#/>But this is in reality very difficult to achieve. <#/>Imported technology is not free of ties precisely because of the expense and interests involved at the initial and subsequent interplay of Research and Develo
pment sub-systems.
\par <#/>To argue that countries like Ghana and Tanzania need not embark on intensive R & D investments because they can transfer what has already been discovered is to under-rate the initial investments on the part of the discoverers to main
tain some technological hegemony.
\par <#/>Worse still, that amounts to the assumption that the R & D system in, say, Britain will easily and freely relate to R & D system in countries like Tanzania and that the output and input will be smooth.
\par <#/>
Western developed countries are now at a stage of computer-aided designs or CADS, which produce integrated technological systems. <#/>The CADS have managed to increase the efficiency of the products as well as being so integrated that no moving wheel or p
arts are seen, as was in the old technology. <#/>Patent protection now becomes less necessary, as it is already very difficult for less developed countries like Tanzania to imitate these "black boxes."
\par <X_>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 Coming to industries, these are vertically integrated into transnational industries }{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 <&/>grammar}{\v\fs24\lang2057 
 than into the domestic market systems and R & D institutions. Most technological inputs are derived from abroad in the form of machines, spare parts and the like. With industrial protectionism, most gadgets com
e in the form of integrated "black boxes" and when one unit becomes defective the whole component system has to be imported. Added to this is the fact that the system of most African governments depends on and consults with donor governments and agencies 
of the west when formulating their developmental policies.
\par In contrast, Western countries' sub-systems of governmental decisional units, educational units, R&D institutions, industrial and the domestic markets maintain symbiotic relationships ... and none can live without the other.
\par Why not so for the African (Third World) sub-systems? Why is there the vertical integration into the world transnational companies' orientation? There is nothing wrong }{\i\v\fs24\lang2057 per se}{\v\fs24\lang2057 
 with this orientation, if only, they were locally integrated first to address local developmental problems and later on deal with international system in competitive exchange relations.
\par Education itself should not be developed for its own sake, and for that matter, neither should the R & D institutions. As a 
sectoral sub-system of the whole governmental system, the Ministry of Education should be organised to take keen cognisance of the short and long-term production objectives of the industrial sector.
\par }\pard\plain \s17\qj\nowidctlpar\tx8364\tx8505\adjustright \v\lang2057 The R & D institutions could draw substantial resources f
rom the Treasury and the industrial sub-systems and the products from such R & D institution would then find applications in the developing industries. Indeed the process of moulding and adapting imported technology would be their concern, and the modifie
d solutions would find their way, into our domestic industries.
\par \pard\plain \qj\nowidctlpar\tx8364\tx8505\adjustright \fs20\lang1031 {\v\fs24\lang2057 
Let us do what the Japanese have done. For, when Japan deals with the Western industrial states, it is on the same plane, as equal partners in a competitive world. The issue becomes what Japan 
