\par }{\fs24\lang2057 <#/>In 1988, the cattle population in Tanzania Mainland stood at around 13 million.
\par <#/>The vast majority of Tanzania's cattle, well over, 90 per cen
t, are indigenous shorthorn Zebu with a few Boran and Ankole. <#/>There is, too, small percentage of exotic and hybrid grade cattle which are confined to government ranches and dairy farms and an increasing number of mostly dairy stock kept by the well-to
-do persons in urban areas.
\par <#/>The vast majority of the indigenous cattle are kept by peasants and pastoralists. <#/>They are well adapted to the environment and need minimum care for their survival. <#/>The exotic and hybrid cattle need a lot of care.
\par <#/>But although the indigenous cattle do well under the climatic conditions of Tanzania, for years they have been kept by the rural people - mostly for a show of wealth. <#/>In this case it is the number which matters.
\par <#/>The sad fact is that, the peasant has actually been a slave of his animals, deriving almost nothing from them, except the assumed prestige. <#/>In view of this the government has been struggling to improve the animals and the lot of the cattle owners.

\par <#/>Experts say that livestock deve
lopment in the country aims at increasing the quantity and quality of livestock and livestock products. <#/>This includes effective control of diseases, the dissemination of improved husbandry practices, land and pasture development.
\par <#/>Nearly all cattle in Dodoma Region belong to the traditional stock and are owned by smallholders and villages. <#/>Animals are kept for a range of financial reasons - but mostly for prestige.
\par <#/>But the livestock keeping tradition in Dodoma region is slowly changing slowly because keepers are now rearing of improved cattle <-/breads> }{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 <&/>grammar}{\fs24\lang2057 
\par <#/>But the region's weather is becoming a problem.
\par <#/>The story of Dodoma region is one of uncertainty. <#/>When the rains fall evenly and in plenty of food, including pasture, are abundant and life is good for both animals and people }{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 <&/>grammar}{\fs24\lang2057 
. <#/>When the rains fall, scarcity or even starvation may follow.
\par <#/>The most difficult time of the year, for c
attle owners, is when the dry season advances into its sixth or seven month. <#/>During that period people keeping animals other than the traditional herd have to travel long distances to fetch green grass so as to get more milk.
\par <#/>But the problem is worse for owners }{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 <+_of>}{\v\fs24\lang2057  }{\fs24\lang2057 the traditional herd who keep many head of cattle.
\par <#/>A livestock official in Dodoma noted recently that cattle destocking in the region had never reached the proposed target. <#/>In 1978, he said, about four per cent of the entire 
cattle population was disposed of while in 1987 it reached about 6.5 per cent. <#/>Dodoma region has 1.1 million head of cattle and a total of about 700,00 goats and sheep. <#/>But the milk supply has never been adequate for the building capital.
\par <#/>Fortunately urban dwellers who have decided to rear improved cattle breeding. <#/>The Ministry of Agriculture and Livestock Development and its institutions should help them.
